==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intern
<hw>In*tern"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>internus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>interne</ets>. See
<er>Internal</er>.]</ety> <def>Internal.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Howell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intern</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Intern
<hw>In*tern"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>interne</ets>. See
<er>Intern</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To put for safe
keeping in the interior of a place or country; to confine to one
locality; <as>as, to <ex>intern</ex> troops which have fled for refuge
to a neutral country</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To hold until the end of a war, as enemy citizens in
a country at the time of outbreak of hostilities; -- an action performed
by countries.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>intern</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: intern
<hw>in*tern"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.]</ety>
<pr>(<it>F. pron.</it> ⟦acr⟧N`t⟦acir⟧rn")</pr> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A resident physician in a hospital, especially
one who has recently received the Doctorate and is practising under
supervision of experienced physicians, as a continuation of the training
process; a house physician; also called <altname>houseman</altname> in
Britain.</def> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>interne</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person working as an apprentice to gain experience
in an occupation; sometimes the position is paid a salary, and other
times it is not; <as>as, a white house <ex>intern</ex>; an
<ex>intern</ex> in a law firm</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Internal</ent>⟦br⟧
